  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka main opposition, dissident MPs to sit out crucial budget vote",
      "author": "Himal Kotelawala",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s main opposition the Samagi Jana Balawegaya (SJB) and a breakaway faction of the ruling Sri Lanka Podujana Peramuna (SLPP) will sit out a vote on President Ranil Wickremesinghe\u2019s interim budget for 2022, the two parties said.",
        "SJB MP Thushara Indunil and SLPP (dissident) MP G L Peiris announced the two parties decision to abstain from voting in separate press briefings on Friday September 02, hours before the vote is to be taken.",
        "Peiris told reporters that the interim budget presented by Wickremesinghe, who is also Finance Minister, contains many \u201cnegative\u201d proposals that are harmful to Sri Lanka. He said while his group of independent MPs do not intend in any way to scuttle Sri Lanka\u2019s ongoing talks with the International Monetary Fund (IMF), but the party retains its right to express its independent views in parliament.",
        "\u201cWe did not get an opportunity express our views on the contents of this interim budget. Taking all this into account, we have decided to abstain from voting this evening,\u201d he said.",
        "Peiris\u2019 faction comprises 13 MPs including Dullas Alahapperuma who ran against Wickremesinghe for the presidency.",
        "MP Indunil meanwhile said the interim budget document does contains no propsals the SJB can support, but though there are grounds for opposing budget, the party won\u2019t be so cruel as to send the wrong message to the world vis-\u00e0-vis the government.",
        "\u201cAs a party, we have decide to neither support nor oppose President Wickremesinghe\u2019s budget and to abstain from voting instead,\u201d he said.",
        "Political analysts say the main opposition\u2019s and the independent MPs\u2019 moves to sit out the crucial budget vote will throw a spanner in the works of the president\u2019s repeated attempts to form an all-party government.",
        "Delivering the interim budget speech in parliament on Tuesday August 30, he reiterated the call, highlighting the importance of political stability bipartisan consensus in seeing Sri Lanka through much needed economic reforms.",
        "Meanwhile, former Sports Minister and SLPP MP Namal Rajapaksa, who is reportedly involved in efforts to revive the SLPP, said on Thursday that President Wickremesinghe ought to form a stable administration with the 134 ruling party MPs who elected him rather than pin his hopes on an all-party government.",
        "Sri Lanka president should form stable govt with SLPP: MP Namal Rajapaksa"
      ],
